"contributions","id":"16100"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44170"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49747","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49747"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-year-old boy is referred to a paediatrician by his General Practitioner due to parental concerns about his development. He was born at term after an uncomplicated pregnancy and delivery. He has no significant medical history. His mother reports that he has had delayed speech and poor eye contact since infancy. On examination, his height and weight are at the 50th percentile. Genetic testing reveals a deletion at 16p11.2.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following conditions is this child most likely to be diagnosed with?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fragile X syndrome","Rett syndrome","Tuberous sclerosis","Down syndrome","Autism spectrum disorder"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDeletions in the 16p11.2 region are one of the most common genetic abnormalities associated with \u003Cstrong\u003Eautism spectrum disorder (ASD)\u003C/strong\u003E. Approximately 1% of patients with ASD have a deletion in this region. The clinical features described in the stem, including poor eye contact and delayed speech, are consistent with a diagnosis of ASD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFragile X syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common inherited cause of intellectual disability and is also associated with ASD. However, it is caused by an expansion of a CGG trinucleotide repeat in the FMR1 gene on the X chromosome, not a deletion at 16p11.2.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERett syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare genetic disorder that primarily affects girls and is characterized by normal early development followed by a slowing of development, loss of purposeful use of the hands, distinctive hand movements, slowed brain and head growth, problems with walking, seizures, and intellectual disability. It is most commonly caused by mutations in the MECP2 gene.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETuberous sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare genetic disease in which several different organ systems can be involved. Non-cancerous tumours can be found in the brain, kidneys, heart, eyes, lungs and the skin. Symptoms may include seizures, intellectual disability and behavioural problems.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDown syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a genetic disorder (trisomy 21). It is usually associated with characteristic facial features, mild to moderate intellectual disability, and an increased risk of various health problems.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Deletion of 16p11.2 is associated with an increased risk of autism spectrum disorder."],"references":["Taylor CM, Smith R, Lehman C, et al. 16p11.2 Recurrent Deletion. In: Adam MP, Feldman J, Mirzaa GM, et al., editors. GeneReviews\u00ae [Internet]. 2009 Sep 22 [Updated 2021 Oct 28]. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK11167/","Fetit R, Price DJ, Lawrie SM, Johnstone M. Understanding the clinical manifestations of 16p11.2 deletion syndrome: a series of developmental case reports in children. Psychiatr Genet. 2020;30(5):136-140. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7497286/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35001"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13736"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35001","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35001"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-03T16:03:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-28T17:06:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6355"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49747"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}}